{"can_edit": true, "from": {"name": "Micha\u00ebl Caron Couturier", "id": "1646843124"}, "revision": "10152826253305019", "updated_time": "2013-04-25T05:23:54+0000", "can_delete": true, "created_time": "2012-04-08T20:23:40+0000", "message": "<p>Time to show off some love to the favorite distro of the group, isn&#039;t it?? ;)</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Note : Adapted more than possible for beginners...</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Installation guides:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/Official_Installation_Guide</p>\n<p>http://wiki.archlinux.fr/Installation *french/fran\u00e7ais*</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Less up-to-date installation guides but worth a look:</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>http://lifehacker.com/5680453/build-a-killer-customized-arch-linux-installation-and-learn-all-about-linux-in-the-process *easier*</p>\n<p>http://willensky.blogspot.ca/2010/01/how-to-setup-arch-linux.html *further install*</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Recommended cheat-sheets:</em></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>http://i.imgur.com/JB6N5.jpg - really worth a look</p>\n<p>http://img.docstoccdn.com/thumb/orig/14992490.png - *outdated after systemd*<br /></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Recommended AUR helpers:</em></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Yaourt - Install it from AUR<br /></p>\n<p>Packer - Add it by Yaourt</p>\n<p>(Add numbers of packages wanted with spaces between them, don&#039;t edit files if you don&#039;t know what to do)</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Package management made easy:</em></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>sudo pacman -U /packagefolder/package.tar.xz = <em>install package offline<br /></em>\n<p>sudo pacman -Syy = <em>sync mirrors after pacman.conf/mirrorlist changes</em></p>sudo pacman -Q &gt; list.txt = <em>list all installed packages in the list.txt file</em>\n<p>sudo pacman -R package1 package2 = <em>remove packages</em></p>\n<p>sudo pacman -Rdns package1 package2 = <em>remove packages, dependencies, configuration</em></p>\n<p>yaourt -Sy package1 package2 --tmp /home/mike/Desktop/Aur = <em>install bigger packages that may be too big for /tmp (don&#039;t forget to empty your /tmp before)<br /></em></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><em>Configuration Files:</em></p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Pacman</strong></p>\n<p>/etc/rc.conf Main configuration file for modules, daemons, network, etc. *deprecated after introduction of systemd*<br /></p><p>/etc/locale.gen     Locale Config</p>\n<p>/etc/makepkg.conf     Makepkg configuarion</p>\n<p>file/etc/pacman.conf    Pacman config</p>\n<p>file/etc/abs.conf     ABS config</p>\n<p>file/etc/mkinitcpio.conf    Initrd cofiguration</p>\n<p>/etc/conf.d/    Daemons configuration *deprecated after systemd*<br />/etc/pacman.d/    Mirrors config for pacman</p>\u00a0\n<p><strong>Xorg configuration</strong></p>\n<p>pacman -S xorg    Installs xorg</p>\n<p>pacman -Ss xf86-video    List generic  video drivers</p>\n<p>Xorg -configurenvidia-xconfig    Configure a xorg.conf  file [New versions of Xorg should detect everything, install hal with  pacman and then try startx] In order to boot in X you should add a login  manager to the daemons array (GDM, Slim, Kdm), use the startx script or  change the initlevel and login manager in /etc/inittab</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Useful man pages:</strong> xorg.conf, inittab, pacman.conf, pacman, makepkg, packer, yaourt, useradd, gpasswd, groups</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Useful Groups</strong></p>\n<p>gpasswd -a user group Add user to group</p>\n<p>lp  For printers</p>\n<p>audio    For audio</p>\n<p>optical    Access to optical drives</p>\n<p>storage   Access to storage devices</p>\n<p>video    Access to video devices <br /></p><p><br /></p>\n<p><strong>Other Common Packages</strong></p>\n<p>pacman -S ttf-ms-fonts ttf-dejavu ttf-bitstream-vera    Some fonts</p>\n<p>pacman -S gnome gnome-extra gdm    Installs Gnome, extra apps and the GDM login manager</p>\n<p>pacman -S elinks    Text mode browser</p>\n<p>pacman -S firefox jre flashplugin     Installs Firefox with JRE and Adobe Flash plugins</p>\n<p>pacman -S vimdiff    Useful to check differences betwen files, like a .pacnew config file</p>\n<p>pacman -S alsa-lib alsa-utils    Installs alsa, then run alsaconfig</p>\n<p>pacman -S codecs gstreamer0.10-bad gstreamer0.10-ugly gstreamer0.10-ffmpeg gstreamer0.10-ugly-plugins    Propietary codecs</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p><strong>Links and informations :</strong></p>\n<p>Forum:</p>\n<p>http://bbs.archlinux.org</p>\n<p>Wiki: http://wiki.archlinux.org</p>\n<p>Aur: http://aur.archlinux.org</p>\n<p>IRC: #archlinux, #archlinux-offtopic at Freenode</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Use man &#039;&lt;command&gt;&#039; to get the manual pages. In some cases, a given tool may have more than one man page, to access all of them use &#039;man -a &lt;command&gt;&#039; or &#039;man N &lt;command&gt;&#039; if you know which page it is.</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Search the web, the wiki and forums at any troubles</p>\n<p>Always check .pacnew files after upgrades<br /></p>\n<p>Always read news and forum before a full system update</p>\n<p>Check logs for important messages and errors (/var/log/)</p>\n<p>Read the PKGBUILD before install any software from AUR</p>\n<p>\u00a0</p>\n<p>Thanks for reading, please submit suggestions/additions/changes ... if the document seem unclear.<br />For Archlinux beginners, begin with Bridge-Linux Light *website: millertechnologies.bet*. It may seem that I advertise for someone that I know but it seems to be the best Archlinux customisation (for me atleast) to begin with and remember that we are here to help if needed. Just seek the arch wiki/forums and google before a little, Arch is pretty easy after installation so most of us shouldn&#039;t have much troubles with it.</p>", "subject": "Archlinux cheatsheet", "id": "10151512100545019", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yi/r/-64q65AWgXb.png"}